---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro'
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About — Image Tools"
  description="Why image.oriz.in exists and how it works under the hood."
>
  <header class="container-prose page-head">
    <p class="eyebrow"><a href="/">Image Tools</a> / About</p>
    <h1>About Image Tools</h1>
  </header>

  <article class="container-prose prose">
    <p class="lede">
      <strong>image.oriz.in</strong> is a free collection of image-processing
      tools that run entirely in your browser. No uploads, no servers handling
      your photos, no tracking pixels embedded in the output.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this exists</h2>
    <p>
      Most "free" image tools online upload your photos to a server, run
      whatever processing they offer, and email you (or worse, train models on
      what you sent). That's a privacy tradeoff we don't need anymore — modern
      browsers can do almost all of this work locally with WebAssembly,
      Canvas APIs, and ONNX runtimes.
    </p>

    <h2>How it works</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Compression</strong> — <code>browser-image-compression</code>
        with native Canvas encoding for JPG/PNG/WebP.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Format conversion</strong> — <code>heic2any</code> for HEIC,
        Canvas for everything else.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Background removal</strong> — <code>@imgly/background-removal</code>
        running an ONNX model in a Web Worker.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>AI upscaling</strong> — Real-ESRGAN ONNX models, browser-side.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Face blur</strong> — <code>face-api.js</code> with TinyFaceDetector,
        purely client-side.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Photo editor</strong> — <code>fabric.js</code> for the canvas
        editing surface.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Part of the oriz family</h2>
    <p>
      Image Tools is one of ten sites under <a href="https://oriz.in">oriz.in</a> —
      a personal family of static sites by Chirag Singhal. One sign-in (optional)
      works across every site. See the rest at
      <a href="https://oriz.in">oriz.in</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Open source</h2>
    <p>
      The repo lives at
      <a href="https://github.com/chirag127/oriz-image-tools">github.com/chirag127/oriz-image-tools</a>.
      Issues, PRs, and feature requests welcome.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
